WEBVTT

00:00:06.970 --> 00:00:07.360
PROFESSOR: Hi.

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:09.010
Welcome back to recitation.

00:00:09.010 --> 00:00:12.550
We've been talking in lecture
about various different

00:00:12.550 --> 00:00:14.840
applications of definite
integrals.

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:17.450
And one of them has been that we
can use definite integrals

00:00:17.450 --> 00:00:20.770
to find areas of regions that
previously we wouldn't have

00:00:20.770 --> 00:00:21.550
been able to.

00:00:21.550 --> 00:00:25.710
So, one simple example of that
is that we can use a definite

00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:28.210
integral to find the
area of a region

00:00:28.210 --> 00:00:29.850
bounded between two curves.

00:00:29.850 --> 00:00:32.320
So I have an example of such
a question right here.

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:35.000
So the question is to compute
the area of the region that's

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.780
bounded between the curves
y equals x cubed and y

00:00:38.780 --> 00:00:40.930
equals 3x minus 2.

00:00:40.930 --> 00:00:44.190
So one thing you'll notice is I
haven't given you endpoints

00:00:44.190 --> 00:00:44.940
for this region.

00:00:44.940 --> 00:00:46.880
So I've just given you
the bound and curves.

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:48.480
So one thing you're going to
have to do right at the

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:53.400
beginning is to figure out what
this looks like and what

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:55.040
region you're going to
be integrating over.

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:57.330
What interval you're going
to be integrating over.

00:00:57.330 --> 00:00:59.880
So, this is a kind
of tricky one.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:01.750
Why don't you pause the video,
think about it for a few

00:01:01.750 --> 00:01:04.310
minutes, try and work it out
yourself, and you can come

00:01:04.310 --> 00:01:05.960
back and we can try and
work it out together.

00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:16.250
All right, welcome back.

00:01:16.250 --> 00:01:19.820
So hopefully you've had some
luck figuring out what this

00:01:19.820 --> 00:01:22.870
situation looks like and then
computing the integral.

00:01:22.870 --> 00:01:25.280
So let's talk about
it for a minute.

00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:27.020
So we have these two curves.

00:01:27.020 --> 00:01:28.710
And so somewhere--

00:01:28.710 --> 00:01:32.340
I'm asking about the region
bounded by them-- so what I'm

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:35.380
telling you is somewhere these
curves intercept and they

00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:38.290
surround some bounded region.

00:01:38.290 --> 00:01:41.860
And so I'm asking for what the
area of that region is.

00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:45.780
So in order to figure that
out, we should figure out

00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:47.700
where these curves intercept.

00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:50.430
So to find the, in other words,
we need to find the

00:01:50.430 --> 00:01:52.140
endpoints of the interval
over which

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:54.150
we're going to integrate.

00:01:54.150 --> 00:01:57.840
So in order to that, we have to
solve for where we have the

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:00.840
intersection between y
equals x cubed and y

00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:02.430
equals 3x minus 2.

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:04.860
So we have to solve
the equation.

00:02:04.860 --> 00:02:13.700
So we need to solve the
equation x cubed

00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:14.990
equals 3x minus 2.

00:02:14.990 --> 00:02:20.230
Or x cubed minus 3x
plus 2 equals 0.

00:02:20.230 --> 00:02:21.900
So this a polynomial equation.

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:23.150
It's not quadratic, right?

00:02:23.150 --> 00:02:24.610
It's a cubic equation.

00:02:24.610 --> 00:02:27.580
So that means it's hard
to solve in general.

00:02:27.580 --> 00:02:30.520
Luckily in this case, it's,
there are some, there's a root

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:32.550
we can recognize
fairly easily.

00:02:32.550 --> 00:02:34.740
Which is, it's pretty,
you know,--

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:38.460
one thing you can always do is
check small positive integers

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:41.120
or use the rational root
theorem, if you remember that

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:43.720
from high school math.

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:47.210
So in this case, if you check
x equals 1, it's fairly easy

00:02:47.210 --> 00:02:50.230
to see that x equals 1 is
a root of this equation.

00:02:50.230 --> 00:02:52.710
So in other words, we can factor
the left-hand side.

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:57.870
We can divide out a factor
of x minus 1.

00:02:57.870 --> 00:03:01.780
OK, and so now we have to do
long division or synthetic

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:05.220
division, whatever kind of
division you want to divide

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:05.670
through here.

00:03:05.670 --> 00:03:11.520
So we get x squared minus--

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:14.830
so we've got a nope, I lied.

00:03:14.830 --> 00:03:21.570
Plus x minus 2 after
you divide.

00:03:21.570 --> 00:03:23.340
How's that look?

00:03:23.340 --> 00:03:23.956
We can just double-check.

00:03:23.956 --> 00:03:28.180
You know, we get an x cubed
minus x squared plus x squared

00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:31.580
minus 2x minus x plus 2.

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:32.510
OK.

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:33.760
So that adds up to
the right thing.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:39.129
So we either have that 1 is a
root or that x squared you

00:03:39.129 --> 00:03:45.080
know, rather for the places
where these intersect, we have

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:48.540
either x equals 1 or x squared
plus x minus 2 equals 0.

00:03:48.540 --> 00:03:52.730
And now here you can, you know,
again factor or use the

00:03:52.730 --> 00:03:54.820
quadratic equation
or what have you.

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:57.830
And you can see so we have
that this actually fully

00:03:57.830 --> 00:04:03.520
factors as x minus 1 squared
times x plus 2 equals 0.

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:11.940
Which means that we have
intersections when either x

00:04:11.940 --> 00:04:14.440
minus 1 is 0 or when
x plus 2 is 0.

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:23.446
So intersections at x equals
1 and x equals minus 2.

00:04:23.446 --> 00:04:25.650
All right.

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:28.010
So you can take that information
and you can, you

00:04:28.010 --> 00:04:30.170
know, put it together and
you can make a nice

00:04:30.170 --> 00:04:30.820
picture like this.

00:04:30.820 --> 00:04:33.090
Or, I suppose, you could have
made the nice picture before

00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:34.990
you had that information.

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:37.500
And so we see that we've
got this line, y

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.790
equals 3x minus 2 here.

00:04:39.790 --> 00:04:42.160
And we have the curve
y equals x cubed.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:43.490
And they have two intersection
points.

00:04:43.490 --> 00:04:44.620
They intersect once.

00:04:44.620 --> 00:04:47.280
Down at x equals minus
2, y equals minus 8.

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:50.790
And they intersect again
up at the point 1, 1.

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:52.280
And they're actually
tangent there.

00:04:52.280 --> 00:04:57.300
So x cubed, the curve y equals
x cubed stays above the line

00:04:57.300 --> 00:04:58.230
at this point.

00:04:58.230 --> 00:05:01.310
So one way you can read that off
is here you had a double

00:05:01.310 --> 00:05:03.513
root at minus 1, if you like.

00:05:03.513 --> 00:05:11.660
But, OK, so then, the
region in question

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:12.670
is this region here.

00:05:12.670 --> 00:05:17.550
So it's a region bounded between
those two curves that

00:05:17.550 --> 00:05:19.290
we're trying to compute
the area of.

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:21.960
So now that we have the
endpoints this isn't such a

00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:22.885
tricky problem at all.

00:05:22.885 --> 00:05:23.310
Right?

00:05:23.310 --> 00:05:25.760
so we've got the endpoints
and we know--

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:28.390
now that we've drawn this
picture-- we know which curve

00:05:28.390 --> 00:05:30.205
is on top and which curve
is on bottom.

00:05:30.205 --> 00:05:31.070
Right?

00:05:31.070 --> 00:05:35.090
So the height, when we imagine
cutting this region into lots

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:38.470
of little rectangles or
approximate rectangles, the

00:05:38.470 --> 00:05:43.450
height is going to be x cubed
minus 3x minus 2.

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:45.100
Minus the quantity 3x minus 2.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:45.610
Right?

00:05:45.610 --> 00:05:49.860
The x cubed is on top and 3x
minus 2 is on the bottom.

00:05:49.860 --> 00:05:54.820
So the area is equal
to the integral.

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:57.970
OK, and now we know where we
have to integrate from and to.

00:05:57.970 --> 00:06:01.440
So we're integrating from x
equals minus 2 to 1 to get

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:06.565
this whole region of
x cubed minus the

00:06:06.565 --> 00:06:10.712
quantity 3x minus 2 dx.

00:06:10.712 --> 00:06:12.090
OK?

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:15.610
Because the y equals x cubed
is the top curve.

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:18.430
And y equals 3x minus 2
is the bottom curve.

00:06:18.430 --> 00:06:21.555
So this is the height of those
rectangles, which is positive.

00:06:21.555 --> 00:06:26.030
OK, and so now, OK, well
now this is pretty

00:06:26.030 --> 00:06:26.610
straightforward.

00:06:26.610 --> 00:06:29.160
We're integrating a polynomial
at this point.

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:31.530
So this is the integral.

00:06:31.530 --> 00:06:36.330
Well, OK, so integrating x
cubed, that gives me x to the

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:38.760
fourth over 4.

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:44.540
Integrating minus 3x gives me
minus 3x squared over 2.

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:51.030
And integrating plus 2 gives
me plus 2x between x equals

00:06:51.030 --> 00:06:53.030
minus 2 and 1.

00:06:53.030 --> 00:06:55.350
So OK, so now I just
do this difference.

00:06:55.350 --> 00:07:04.520
So this is equal to 1/4 minus
3/2 plus 2 minus--

00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:08.550
OK, now I put in minus 2 I get
2 to the fourth-- sorry--

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:13.970
minus 2 to the fourth is 16
over 4, so that's minus 4.

00:07:13.970 --> 00:07:19.020
OK, minus 3 times
4 over 2 is 6.

00:07:19.020 --> 00:07:24.510
And then plus 2 times minus
2 is minus 4 again.

00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:26.150
OK, and now we've just
got some arithmetic.

00:07:26.150 --> 00:07:29.600
So this all becomes a plus 6.

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:32.700
And I have to add everything
together.

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:37.090
So that's something like, well
I've got a denominator of 4,

00:07:37.090 --> 00:07:39.390
so it's, yeah.

00:07:39.390 --> 00:07:41.750
All right, so there's a secret
I should tell you.

00:07:41.750 --> 00:07:45.010
Which is that mathematicians are
not actually very good at

00:07:45.010 --> 00:07:46.540
arithmetic, usually.

00:07:46.540 --> 00:07:55.520
So this is minus 6/4 plus
2 plus 6, so plus 8.

00:07:55.520 --> 00:08:03.160
So this is 8 minus 5/4,
which is 6 and 3/4.

00:08:03.160 --> 00:08:06.150
OK, that's 6 plus 3/4.

00:08:06.150 --> 00:08:07.800
So 6 and 3/4.

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:09.460
This was just arithmetic.

00:08:09.460 --> 00:08:11.420
Here was the calculus part.

00:08:11.420 --> 00:08:15.650
And, in fact, you know, one
feature of a problem like this

00:08:15.650 --> 00:08:19.290
is that you have a fair amount
of work sometimes to see the

00:08:19.290 --> 00:08:21.740
picture of what you're
working with.

00:08:21.740 --> 00:08:23.530
Then the integration here was
pretty straightforward.

00:08:23.530 --> 00:08:24.630
Right?

00:08:24.630 --> 00:08:26.820
This was a fairly easy
integral to compute.

00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:30.850
If you're, say, better at
fraction arithmetic than I am,

00:08:30.850 --> 00:08:33.050
at least.

00:08:33.050 --> 00:08:35.250
So, there you go.

00:08:35.250 --> 00:08:37.150
So, we had this region.

00:08:37.150 --> 00:08:39.940
So we found, actually the
endpoints of the interval.

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:41.520
We found which was the
top curve and which

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:42.550
was the bottom curve.

00:08:42.550 --> 00:08:44.350
And that led us right
down this integral.

00:08:44.350 --> 00:08:46.900
And then that integral was
fairly easy to compute from

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:48.080
that point out.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:50.710
And then we ended up with
this as our final area.

00:08:50.710 --> 00:08:52.380
So I'll end there.